28925a98-51b6-405a-96fd-e2900be34ab5.07e95c3a-6e3c-4db6-aa3d-b9378f884a52.description=
This operation does not do anything. It can be used to filter flow variables by defining them as inputs and filtering them in the Results tab.

Inputs\:
    field1 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field2 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field3 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field4 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of  "field1" as it was specified at input or when filtered. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
28925a98-51b6-405a-96fd-e2900be34ab5.2a0e1f1c-7b34-4cb0-aa38-a945d0d109ba.description=
Offsets the current date and time by a given number of units. If locale is specified, the date and time will be in the format based on the locale. Otherwise, default locale will be used. 

Inputs\:
    units - The number of units to offset by. If this is positive, the offset goes into the future, if it is negative the offset goes into the past.
    secondsPerUnit - The number of seconds per unit. This defaults to 1 hour, thus the units is by default measured in hours.
    localeLang - The locale language for date and time string.
Examples;  en, ja, unix.
    localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ingored.

Returns\:
    The offset date/time. 

Responses\:
    success - Operation completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Notes.
    1. If you need the output to be a UNIX timestamp, use the value 'unix' for localeLang. In this case, the localeCountry input will be ignored and the result of the operation will be in UNIX format.
28925a98-51b6-405a-96fd-e2900be34ab5.42f468f9-033d-4c1b-9340-c3db8e34be32.description=
Changes the time represented by a date by the specified number of seconds. If locale is specified, it will return the date and time string based on the locale. Otherwise, default locale will be used.

Inputs\:
    date - The date and time to modify, formatted as provided by Get Current Date and Time.
    offset - The number of seconds to change date by.
    localeLang - The locale language for date and time string. 
Examples\:  en, ja, unix.
    localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ingored.

returns\:
    A new date and time, formatted the same as the input.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Notes.
    1. If you need to offset a UNIX date, use the value 'unix' for localeLang. In this case, the localeCountry input will be ignored and the result of the operation will be in UNIX format.
28925a98-51b6-405a-96fd-e2900be34ab5.497a47eb-4a07-4ed3-a406-455f1633ad58.description=
Check the current date and time, and returns a java DateAndTime formatted string of it. If locale is specified, it will return the date and time string based on the locale.Otherwise, default locale will be used.

Inputs\:
    localeLang - The locale language for date and time string. 
Examples\:  en, ja, unix.
    localeCountry - The locale country for date and time string. For example, US or JP. If localeLang is not specified, this input will be ingored.

Result\:
    Current date and time.

Responses\:
    success - Date/time retrieved successfully.   
    failure - Date/time could not be retrieved.

Notes.
    1. If localeLang is 'unix' the localeCountry input is ignored and the result will be the current UNIX timestamp.
28925a98-51b6-405a-96fd-e2900be34ab5.a7cb801e-e23e-4a33-a954-a422dd02b061.description=
This operation converts the date input value from one date/time format (specified by dateFormat) to another date/time format (specified by outFormat) using locale settings (language and country).
You can use the flow "Get Current Date and Time" to check upon the default date/time format from the Java environement.  

Inputs\:
    date - The date to parse/convert.
    dateFormat - The format of the input date.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    dateLocaleLang - The locale language for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    dateLocaleCountry - The locale country for input dateFormat string. It will be ignored if dateFormat is empty or dateLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR
    outFormat - The format of the output date/time.
Default value\: default date/time format from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS date/time format)
Examples\: unix, yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX, h\:mm a
    outLocaleLang - The locale language for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty. 
Default value\: default locale language from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale language)
Examples\: en, ja
    outLocaleCountry - The locale country for output string. It will be ignored if outFormat is empty or outLocaleLang is empty.
Default value\: default locale country from the Java environement (which is dependent on the OS locale country)
Example\: US, FR

Results\:
    returnResult - The date in the new format.

Responses\:
    success - The date was converted.
    failure - The date could not be converted.

Notes\:
    1. If default locale language from the Java environement is English, the input dateFormat is empty and the input outFormat is empty, the input date should be in the format of "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the user specifies dateFormat as "dd-MM-YYYY HH\:mm\:ss", the input date should be in the format of "13-07-2006 10\:04\:08". If the input outFormat is empty, the result will be "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:08 AM". If the input outFormat is "yyyy-MM-dd", the result will be "2006-07-13". The dateFormat for "July 13, 2006 10\:04\:078 AM" is "MMM dd, yyyy HH\:mm\:ss a".
    2. Note that the dateFormat and outFormat inputs are case sensitive. 'M' is used for months representation and 'm' for minutes.
    3. Within date and time pattern strings, unquoted letters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are interpreted as pattern letters representing the components of a date or time string. Text can be quoted using single quotes (') to avoid interpretation. "''" represents a single quote. All other characters are not interpreted; they're simply copied into the output string during formatting or matched against the input string during parsing. The following pattern letters are defined (all other characters from 'A' to 'Z' and from 'a' to 'z' are reserved)\:

Letter	Date or Time Component			Presentation		Examples
G	Era designator				Text		AD
y	Year				Year		1996; 96
Y	Week year				Year		2009; 09
M	Month in year				Month		July; Jul; 07
w	Week in year				Number		27
W	Week in month				Number		2
D	Day in year				Number		189
d	Day in month				Number		10
F	Day of week in month			Number		2
E	Day name in week			Text		Tuesday; Tue
u	Day number of week (1 \= Monday, ..., 7 \= Sunday)	Number		1
a	Am/pm marker				Text		PM
H	Hour in day (0-23)			Number		0
k	Hour in day (1-24)			Number		24
K	Hour in am/pm (0-11)			Number		0
h	Hour in am/pm (1-12)			Number		12
m	Minute in hour				Number		30
s	Second in minute			Number		55
S	Millisecond				Number		978
z	Time zone				General time zone	Pacific Standard Time; PST; GMT-08\:00
Z	Time zone				RFC 822 time zone	-800
X	Time zone				ISO 8601 time zone	-08; -0800; -08\:00
Special case\:
unix	Unix timestamp			Number		1384326000

Examples for the date 2001-07-04 12\:08\:56 in U.S. Pacific Time\:

Date			DateFromat			DateLocaleLang	DateLocaleCountry
2001.07.04 AD at 12\:08\:56 PDT	yyyy.MM.dd G 'at' HH\:mm\:ss z		en		US
Wed, Jul 4, '01			EEE, MMM d, ''yy		en		US
2001-07-04T12\:08\:56.235+0700	yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSZ	en		US
2001-07-04T12\:08\:56.235-07\:00	yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH\:mm\:ss.SSSXXX	en		US
1309781336			unix			-		-
28925a98-51b6-405a-96fd-e2900be34ab5.ac1b2f88-dcdd-4478-8d08-6edcde4600c0.description=
Service to perform HTTP POST using the Java HTTP Client.

Inputs\:
    url - The URL to POST to.
    characterSet -  The character encoding to be used for the HTTP POST request and response.
Default value\: UTF-8
    username - The user name used for URL authentication. For NTLM authentication, the required format is 'domain\user'.
    password - The password used for URL authentication.
    authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server.
Valid values\: basic, form, springForm, digest, ntlm, kerberos, anonymous (no authentication).
Default value\: anonymous - authentication not used when executing the request.
    kerberosConfFile - The  path to the Kerberos configuration file. If this input is empty, the "kdc" (Key Distribution Center) and "realm" get their values from the full domain name obtained from the web server URL.
    inputNameList - The list containing the names of inputs to use for the post operation.
    inputValueList - The list containing the values of inputs to use for the operation MUST be the same length as the list of names.
    proxy - The proxy server used to access the web site.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port.
Default value\: 8080
    proxyUsername - The proxy server user name.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the "proxyUsername" input value.
    userAgent - The value to use if the 'USER_AGENT' HTTP header has to be overwritten.
    useCookies - Specifies whether to enable cookie tracking or not. Cookies are stored between consecutive calls. If you specify a non-Boolean value, the default value is used.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true
    timeout - The time to wait for a connection to be established, in  milliseconds. 
Valid values\: This input needs a value greater than or equal to zero. A "timeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
    socketTimeout - The time to wait for data to be retrieved, in milliseconds. 
Valid values\: This input needs a value greater than or equal to zero. A "socketTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
    encodeURL - Specifies whether to encode the URL. If you specify a non-Boolean value, the default value is used.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL. A SSL certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true
    x509HostnameVerifier - Specifies the way the server hostname must match a domain name in the subject's Common Name (CN) or subjectAltName field of the X.509 certificate. The hostname verification system prevents communication with other hosts other than the ones you intended. This is done by checking that the hostname is in the subject alternative name extension of the certificate. This system is designed to ensure that, if an attacker(Man In The Middle) redirects traffic to his machine, the client will not accept the connection. If you set this input to "allow_all", this verification is ignored and you become vulnerable to security attacks. For the value "browser_compatible" the hostname verifier works the same way as Curl and Firefox. The hostname must match either the first CN, or any of the subject-alts. A wildcard can occur in the CN, and in any of the subject-alts. The only difference between "browser_compatible" and "strict" is that a wildcard (such as "*.foo.com") with "browser_compatible" matches all subdomains, including "a.b.foo.com". From the security perspective, to provide protection against possible Man-In-The-Middle attacks, we strongly recommend to use "strict" option.
Default value\: allow_all
Valid values\: strict,browser_compatible,allow_all
    keystore - The location of the KeyStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS client authentication is used. The default value will be provided if "trustAllRoots" is "false".
Default value\: /java/lib/security/cacerts
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file. If "trustAllRoots" is "false" and "keystore" is empty, "keystorePassword" default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    trustKeystore - The location of the TrustStore file - a URL or the local path to it. This input is empty if no HTTPS server authentication is used. The default value will be provided if "trustAllRoots" is "false".
Default\: /java/lib/security/cacerts
    trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file. If "trustAllRoots" is "false" and "trustKeystore" is empty, "trustPassword" default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    headerNamesList - The list containing the header names to use for the request.
Example\: Accept,Content-Type
    headerValuesList - The list containing the header values to use for the request. 
Example\: text/plain,application/x-www-form-urlencoded
    queryNamesList - The list containing the names of the query parameters to use for the request. 
Example\: parameterName1,parameterName2 
    queryValuesList - The list containing the values of the query parameters to use for the request. 
Example\: parameterValue1,parameterValue2
    delimiter - The delimiter used to separates list elements.
Default value\: ','

Results\: 	
    FailureMessage - This is the primary output. The final error message returned to the user.
    resultText - The raw result of the operation.
    document - The complete document returned by the Http Client Post operation.
    URL - The URL to POST to.
    pageLoadTimeInMS - The time it took the page to load, in milliseconds.
    responseTimeInMS - The time it took the server to respond, in milliseconds.
    errorMessage - An informational message that can help determine the cause of error, if an error occurred.
    httpResult - The description of the HTTP response returned by the web server for the request sent by this operation. This result contains the HTTP response status or GENERAL_ERROR if the HTTP request could not be executed.
Examples\: SUCCESS, PAGE_NOT_FOUND, UNAUTHORIZED, FORBIDDEN and so on.
    responseHeaders - The list containing the headers of the response message, separated by "delimiter".
    status - The HTTP response code.
Example\: HTTP/1.1 200 OK
    exception - If an error occurred, the stack trace of the thrown error.

Responses\:
    INFORMATIONAL - The POST was not fully processed, the server responded with an informational response.
    REDIRECTION - The specified URL has moved.
    PAGE_NOT_FOUND - The url specified to POST from could not be found.
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Notes\:
1. You can use KeyTool to import a SSL certificate in a KeyStore. For example, to import a certificate in the Java cacerts KeyStore, run\: keytool -import -file c\:/../.cer -alias  -keystore /java/lib/security/cacerts -keystorepass changeit. If the KeyStore does not exist, the command tries to create a new one containing only your certificate.
2. You can use KeyTool to create a certificate chain through the following command\: 
   keytool -genkey -dname "cn\=Mark Jones, ou\=JavaSoft, o\=Sun, c\=US" 
      -alias business -keypass kpi135 -keystore C\:\working\mykeystore 
      -storepass ab987c -validity 180
This creates a certificate chain in a new KeyStore containing only one certificate. It is useful in SSL client authentication because the KeyManager ignores any certificates not included in a certificate chain.
3. If the value assigned to the "trustAllRoots" input is "false" and "trustKeystore" is empty, the operation tries to use the default trust store, using the password "changeit". 
4. If the authentication type is Kerberos, you might need to add an SPN (Service Principal Name) for the web server's computer account.  In order to do this, you can use ADUC (Active Directory Users and Computers) with enabled 'Advanced Features'. Go to the web server's computer account (example\: CN\=,CN\=Computers,DC\=domain,DC\=com), open the 'Properties' window and press the 'Attribute Editor' tab. Observe the values of the 'servicePrincipalName' attribute and add your SPN if not present. For example, HTTP/\:port.
5. If you need to specify the request header fields, use the "headerNamesList" and "headerValuesList" inputs. The operation also accepts hidden inputs whose names begin with "header_", but this deprecated. You can add multiple headers.  For example, add an input name called "header_Content-Type" with a "text/htm"' value and/or an input name called "header_Content-Length" with a "348" value.  The operation strips off the "header_" prefix from the input name and then creates the "Content-Type" and/or "Content-Length" header with the value you specified. If you specify the same header through both the "headerNamesList" and the "header_" hidden inputs, the used value is the one from the "headerValuesList" list, and not from the hidden input.
6. If you need to specify query parameters when making the request, use the "queryNamesList" and "queryValuesList" inputs. The operation also accepts including query parameters in the URL. For example, http\://hostname\:80/page.asp?parameterName1\=parameterValue1¶meterName2\=parameterValue2. If you specify the same query parameter both through the "queryNamesList" and the "url" inputs, the used value is the one from the "queryValuesList", not the one included in the "url".
7. Apache Tomcat is currently the only supported application server when using form-based authentication.

28925a98-51b6-405a-96fd-e2900be34ab5.e5d87c01-6c1a-45f1-a4f2-7afcade7072b.description=
This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
